        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-15043" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-15043" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Your calculations are incorrect.  We donâ€™t determine which tax bracket taxpayers fall into and apply that rate (now 9%) to all of their taxable income.  At present, some of your taxpayerâ€™s income is taxed at 5% (about $5,800), some at 7% (approximately the next $8,500), and the balance at 9%.  The tax (before exemption credits, since I canâ€™t tell how many dependents your fictional taxpayer has), assuming a joint return, on $180K of taxable income (the amount AFTER standard/itemized deductions and some other adjustments) is $11,741.</p>
<p>Letâ€™s assume the following rate structure:  0-$10K, 3%; 10K-17.5K, 5%; 17.5K-25K, 7%; 25K-100K, 9%; 11% over $100K.  Your taxpayerâ€™s tax before exemption credits on $180K would be $16,950.  This isnâ€™t an inconsequential jump, but a taxpayer with $180K of TAXABLE income (which means they very likely have a gross income of at least $200K) isnâ€™t exactly â€œmiddle class.â€  In fact, under the rate structure above, taxpayers wouldnâ€™t actually pay more taxes until their taxable income hit $132,646.  That would seem to provide a lot of tax relief for middle-income and upper-middle income taxpayers.</p>
<p>This doesnâ€™t include the positive effects of changes that Iâ€™ve recommended in the capital gains tax rates for low- and middle-income taxpayers, the adjustments in the standard deduction, and the increase in the exemption credit â€“ which would further reduce taxes on most taxpayers, and eliminate state taxes altogether for those at very low income levels.</p>
